Magic: (def) a power that allows people (such as witches and wizards) to do 
impossible things by saying special words or performing special actions.

Elsa uses hand gestures and movements to control her power. Therefore she 
is using magic. Realistically though, there is no difference between magic 
and powers, except that powers tend to be associated with superheroes and 
are caused by something scientific, such the effect of yellow sun, or a lab 
experiment. Magic tends to be either an innate ability or something that 
can be taught as an innate ability. Magic and powers were both used to 
describe her abilities throughout the movie and are used interchangeably. 
The important point, and the original one I made, is that her abilities are 
not limited to moving or making ice and snow. She can both create and 
control it AND perform other things such as creating sentient beings. This 
would then mean that rather than a psychic ability, cryokenesis, that 
allows her to manipulate ice and snow but would be no more than an very 
specific case of telekinesis, her powers extend much further and could 
accurately be labelled a supernatural phenomenon. The ability to cause 
supernatural phenomenon is most often referred to as magic and in fact 
frequently is within the source. If you want to be semantic, I guess you 
could say what she has are powers but what she does is magic. Both are 
valid, especially given the term magic powers are often shortened to just 
powers or just magic depending on the writers preference. However, do not 
think that because she is not saying spells, or using a cauldron or 
whatever other stereotypical nonsense you associate with magic, does not 
mean that it is magic.
